Intuition
In this problem the key observation is a closing bracket must match its most recent unmatched opening bracket.

when we traverse the string from left to right we dont know when an opening bracket will be closed, so we temporarily store all opening brackets when a closing bracket is encountered , we ensure that it matches it most recent opening bracket , stack is the most ideal data structure as it follows lifo principle, the top of stack always represent most recent unmatched opening bracket .

the stack stores all the opening brackets that are waiting to be matched

if current character is an opening bracket we push it into the stack , if it is a closed bracket the stack must not be empty , and the top of the stack must be itscorresponding opening bracket , if it does we pop it from stack because a new pair is matched ,

if the stack is empty and brackets do not match the string is invalid we immediately return False

after processing all the characters stack should be emoty if not it means there are unmatched opening brackets remaining so string should be empty.

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n) as we traverse the string every character is pushed once onto or popped from stack at most one time

Space complexity:
O(n) in the worst case all characters are opening brackets so stack stores all of them.

Code
class Solution:
    def isValid(self, s: str) -> bool:
        stack = []
        for i in range(len(s)):
            if s[i] == "(" or s[i] == "{" or s[i] == "[":
                stack.append(s[i])
            else:
                if not stack:
                    return False
                elif s[i] == "]" and stack[-1] == '[':
                    stack.pop()
                elif s[i] == ')' and stack[-1] == '(':
                    stack.pop()
                elif s[i] == '}' and stack[-1] == '{':
                    stack.pop()
                else:
                    return False
        if stack :
            return False
        return True
